dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual Five-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for 2000 to 2025 for the national and first-order administrative division levels of Guatemala were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to shapefiles as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Data Base (IDB).
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for Guatemala for 2000-2025 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. President’s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
dataIdInfo.idCredit:
CENSUS DATA 2018 Age-Sex Data: XII Censo Nacional de Población y VII de Vivienda, 2018, Población por Edad y Sexo. Instituto Nacional de Estadística Guatemala. Available online at http://redatam.censopoblacion.gt/bingtm/RpWebEngine.exe/Portal?BASE=CPVGT2018&lang=esp (Indicadores Generales, Personas, Pirámide de población, Nivel de resultado: Municipal, Salida: Tabla, accessed September 02, 2020).
2002 Population Total Data: Censos Nacionales XI de Población y VI de Habitación, 2002, Características de la Población y de los Locales de Habitación Censados, Cuadro A1 - Población Total, Sexo, Grupos de Edad y Área Urbana y Rural, Según Departamento y Municipio. Instituto Nacional de Estadística Guatemala. Available online at http://www.ine.gob.gt/sistema/uploads/2014/02/20/jZqeGe1H9WdUDngYXkWt3GIhUUQCukcg.pdf (accessed September 02, 2020).
The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of non-U.S. census and survey data.
GEOSPATIAL BOUNDARIES International boundaries coincide with the Large Scale International Boundaries (LSIB) dataset from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Available online at http://geonode.state.gov (accessed September 01, 2020). Geospatial data for the first-order administrative divisions of Guatemala were downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange, available online at http://data.humdata.org/dataset/guatemala-administrative-level-0-national-1-departments-and-2-municipalities, "gtm_admbnda_adm2_ocha_conred_20190207" (accessed September 01, 2020).
The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of boundary placements.
NATIONAL ESTIMATES AND PROJECTIONS U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division. International Data Base, December 2019 release, available online at http://www.census.gov/data-tools/demo/idb/informationGateway.php, accessed September 01, 2020.

Consts.useLimit: U.S. Census Bureau population estimates: None. Acknowledgment of the Census Bureau would be appreciated in products derived from its population estimates. The subnational boundaries used for this shapefile were downloaded by the U.S. Census Bureau from a publicly available source for this product. The international boundaries are derived from the Large Scale International Boundaries (LSIB) dataset (public domain).

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS Guatemala's first-order administrative divisions: 22 departamentos as of the 2018 census.
SHAPEFILES The original shapefile downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange had 342 polygons, one for each of Guatemala's 340 second-order administrative divisions (municipios) as reported by the Instituto Nacional de Estadística Guatemala, one for Lago de Amatitlán, and one for Lago de Atitlán. The polygons representing the two lakes were classified as second-order administrative divisions in the original shapefile as part of Guatemala and Sololá departamentos, respectively. No changes were made to the subnational boundaries by USCB staff. The U.S. Census Bureau aligned the shapefile's national boundary to the Large Scale International Boundary Line (LSIB) polygon file from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Finally, the LSIB-aligned shapefile was dissolved into 22 polygons, one for each of Guatemala's first-order administrative divisions (departamentos) as reported by the Instituto Nacional de Estadística Guatemala in the 2018 census.
CENSUS DATA INTERPOLATION The 2002 census totals had the following differences in geography that have been modified to their 2018 locations in the estimates presented here, requiring interpolation and adjustment of 2002 population data by USCB staff: (1) There were a total of 9 new municipios that were formed between Guatemala's 2002 and 2018 censuses, as noted in the USCBCMNT field.
New municipios were each fully formed from part of a single area, and boundaries and population data were not available for the next administrative level down. The total population of the original area in 2002 was divided proportionally according to the populations of the new areas in 2018.
ADDITIONAL NOTES (1) Características de la Población y de los Locales de Habitación Censados was published by the Instituto Nacional de Estadística Guatemala as a scanned PDF document that was not machine-readable. 2002 population totals from this publication were manually transcribed by USCB staff. (2) The USCBCMNT field includes alternate names for some second-order administrative divisions.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS The 2000-2025 population estimates for Guatemala's administrative divisions are provided in the following two tables: (1) The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Guatemala_5yr_age_sex_2000-2025_uscb_nov2020.txt," which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field "GEOMATCH." (2) The Excel table "Guatemala_5yr_age_sex_2000-2025_508_uscb_nov2020.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government's Federal Rehabilitation Act.
Details on processing of the census data and calculation of 2000-2025 estimates are provided in the "Census Metadata" tab of the Excel file and "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas" document. For the subnational areas, the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) "approved" names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in the "Credits") were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country's national statistical office, when available, are entered in the "NSO_CODE" field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternative area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the "USCBCMNT" field. A partial list of the fields in the Excel and Unicode text files, including all fields identifying geographic names and codes, is provided in the Excel file's "Data Dictionary" tab. More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." It includes a data dictionary that is similar to that in the Excel table.
METHODOLOGY For more information, see the following methodology documents in the Spatial Data Repository: (1) "U.S. Census Bureau Methodology for SDR Subnational Population Estimates." (2) "U.S. Census Bureau Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas." (3) "Instructions for Joining Subnational Population Data to Shapefiles."
ACCESS The U.S. Census Bureau’s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the Spatial Data Repository at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/, which also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program. A zipped file containing shapefiles with metadata, an Excel workbook with subnational population estimates, and a Unicode tab-delimited text file is available for each country. PEPFAR products are also available on the Census Bureau website at http://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/demo/international-programs/subnationalpopulation.html for download.
